<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="197" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[833,1505,988,1593]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">
Distribution and biodiversity hotspot: Coastal Peru (
<figureCitation box="[1384,1449,1240,1259]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[114,141,1296,1310]" captionTargetBox="[329,1289,149,1265]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[329,1289,149,1265]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 27. Map of South America with elevational relief and biodiversity hotspots (in grey) showing distribution of Plyomydas adelphe sp. nov. (orange), P. peruviensis (yellow), and P. phalaros sp. nov. (blue). Type localities plotted with square symbols. Map data available in Google Earth KML file 6102and also through GBIF (data-set 7f2de377-9f9f-4276-b0b8-5c792b499223, DOI 10.15468/tiymja)." pageId="5" pageNumber="197">Fig.27</figureCitation>
). Not known to occur in any biodiversity hotspot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="197" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[833,1505,988,1593]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">
Remarks: The description above is based on male specimens only because no females were available for detailed study to provide an updated F* description and inclusion in this manuscript although three specimens (see above) had been studied several years ago and can be unambiguously assigned to this species. Sexual dimorphism is most likely minimal as in the other species and the female terminalia will most likely be identical to 
<taxonomicName authority="Castillo &amp; Dikow, 2017" authorityName="Castillo &amp; Dikow" authorityYear="2017" box="[1406,1503,1462,1482]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Plyomydas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adelphe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1406,1503,1462,1482]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">P. adelphe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[833,910,1491,1510]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Castillo &amp; Dikow, 2017" authorityName="Castillo &amp; Dikow" authorityYear="2017" box="[958,1065,1489,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Plyomydas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalaros" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[958,1065,1489,1509]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">P. phalaros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1070,1148,1491,1510]" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The female specimen in the BMNH (BMNH(E)1202927) was apparently studied by Macquart and labeled 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wilcox &amp; Papavero" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[912,1090,1545,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Mydas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="197" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis box="[912,1090,1545,1565]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="197">Mydas peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but never described as a new species by him.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
